I org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gcat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Political/General News</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gfake"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gcrim"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gpol"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gpir"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Politics/International Relations</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gpol"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001005-20180328-161318"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Top of the News</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Why It Matters; Malaysians wary of fake news law</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Malaysia's proposed anti-fake news law has been received with widespread scepticism, despite the government's repeated assurances that the law will not be used to stifle dissent.</Para><Para>Malaysians are fully aware of the dangers of fake news. But they are also worried about giving the government yet more powers to curb criticism on issues of the day - especially on the eve of a general election.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Officials have shunned debate on the scandal-plagued 1Malaysia Development Berhad (1MDB) in Parliament, and the authorities have put a lid on discussion of issues tied to the state fund.</Para><Para>A whistle-blower was recently sentenced to jail for exposing a multimillion-dollar scandal over government funds in a cattle project, while the alleged perpetrator remains free.</Para><Para>Communications and Multimedia Minister Salleh Said Keruak has sought to appease media personnel whose work may be affected by the law, saying on Monday that articles on 1MDB based on documents by the US Department of Justice won't be considered fake news. He said the proposed law is meant to protect Malaysians from the detrimental harm of viral fake news.</Para><Para>The comments led to sighs of relief among journalists, but given that there are uncertainties over whether other bodies of authority are on the same page, it remains to be seen what could happen once the law is implemented.</Para><Para>The punishments listed in the Bill are seen as harsh. A person deemed guilty could be hauled to prison for up to 10 years, or fined a maximum of RM500,000 (S$169,000), or both. That is 10 times the fine imposed by other existing Malaysian laws governing the spread of false information, and more than three times the prison term. The Bill also allows legal action against those outside Malaysia.</Para><Para>Many will be watching closely to see how the law will be applied.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Trinna Leong </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">An advertisement with the slogan "sharing a lie makes you a liar" at a train station in downtown Kuala Lumpur on March 26, 2018. </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc